{:metadata {:description [{"text" "<p>The nitrate-reducing system, nitrate reductase ([ec:1.7.99.4]), is stimulated by anaerobiosis, nitrate, and nitrite. The NarJ/delta subunit is not part of the nitrate reductase enzyme but is needed for assembly of the multisubunit enzyme complex. In the absence of the delta subunit the core alpha beta enzyme complex is unstable [[cite:PUB00008245]]. The delta subunit is essential for enzyme activity<i>in vivo</i> and<i>in vitro</i>. Although NarJ is required for correct assembly of active enzyme, it dissociates and is not part of the active enzyme. The Escherichia coli (strain K12) NarJ, which is a chaperone required for proper molybdenum cofactor insertion and final assembly of the membrane-bound respiratory nitrate reductase 1. NarJ is required for the insertion of molybdenum into the apo-NarG subunit, maybe by keeping NarG in an appropriate competent-open conformation for the molybdenum cofactor insertion to occur. NarJ maintains the apoNarGH complex in a soluble state. Upon insertion of the molybdenum cofactor, NarJ seems to dissociate from the activated soluble NarGH complex, before its association with the NarI subunit on the membrane [[cite:PUB00053977], [cite:PUB00053978], [cite:PUB00017539]].</p>", "llm" false, "checked" false, "updated" false}], :is-reviewed-llm false, :representative-structure nil, :overlaps-with [{"accession" "IPR036411", "name" "TorD-like superfamily", "type" "homologous_superfamily"}], :member-databases {"panther" {"PTHR43680" "NITRATE REDUCTASE MOLYBDENUM COFACTOR ASSEMBLY CHAPERONE"}, "ncbifam" {"TIGR00684" "nitrate reductase molybdenum cofactor assembly chaperone"}}, :is-updated-llm false, :name {"name" "Nitrate reductase chaperone, NarJ", "short" "NO3_reductase_chaperone_NarJ"}, :wikipedia nil, :source-database "interpro", :type "family", :counters {"structures" 2, "domain_architectures" 0, "proteomes" 1857, "taxa" 8399, "subfamilies" 0, "interactions" 0, "matches" 9433, "sets" 0, "proteins" 94